
00:00:01,170 --> 00:00:02,330
(man) The sharks are back

00:00:02,330 --> 00:00:04,220
in an all-new season
of "Shark Tank,"

00:00:04,220 --> 00:00:07,170
where hopeful entrepreneurs
from across the country

00:00:07,170 --> 00:00:09,400
dream of a chance
to secure an investment

00:00:09,400 --> 00:00:12,150
and gain powerful partners

00:00:12,150 --> 00:00:15,330
to start, grow,
or save their businesses.

00:00:15,330 --> 00:00:17,080
We have five
pending purchase Orders

00:00:17,080 --> 00:00:18,330
for over a million dollars.

00:00:18,330 --> 00:00:20,100
If the sharks
hear a great idea,

00:00:20,100 --> 00:00:23,130
they're ready to invest
using their own money...

00:00:23,130 --> 00:00:25,400
I'm gonna offer you
$200,000.

00:00:25,400 --> 00:00:28,080
And they'll fight each other
for a piece of the action.

00:00:28,080 --> 00:00:30,220
How many brands
have you grown?

00:00:30,220 --> 00:00:33,380
Name the brands
that you have grown.
I just passed
a lemonade stand this morning

00:00:33,380 --> 00:00:35,280
that sells
more product than you.

00:00:35,280 --> 00:00:37,430
But first, the entrepreneurs
must convince a shark

00:00:37,430 --> 00:00:40,470
to invest the full amount
they're asking for,

00:00:40,470 --> 00:00:42,270
or they'll walk away
with nothing.

00:00:42,270 --> 00:00:44,330
So you have access
to retailers?

00:00:44,330 --> 00:00:47,030
I did $6 billion.
B-B-B-Billion.

00:00:47,030 --> 00:00:49,070
It's sink or swim.

00:00:49,070 --> 00:00:51,220
I've never seen a man sweat
as much in my life.

00:00:51,220 --> 00:00:52,370
(laughter)

00:00:53,450 --> 00:00:54,470
Who are the sharks?

00:00:56,270 --> 00:01:00,220
They're self-made millionaire
and billionaire investors

00:01:00,220 --> 00:01:02,350
who are entrepreneurs
themselves.

00:01:04,080 --> 00:01:06,420
Kevin O'Leary
is a venture capitalist

00:01:06,420 --> 00:01:10,000
who turned a $10,000 loan
into a software business

00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:14,280
worth $4.2 billion.

00:01:14,280 --> 00:01:16,450
Lori Greiner,
the queen of QVC,

00:01:16,450 --> 00:01:18,270
holds over 100 patents

00:01:18,270 --> 00:01:20,350
and has launched
over 300 products

00:01:20,350 --> 00:01:22,330
grossing over a half
a billion dollars

00:01:22,330 --> 00:01:24,150
in retail sales.

00:01:24,150 --> 00:01:27,230
Daymond John is a fashion mogul
and branding expert

00:01:27,230 --> 00:01:29,200
who grew his homemade
clothing line

00:01:29,200 --> 00:01:33,250
into the globally recognized
fashion brand Fubu.

00:01:33,250 --> 00:01:36,320
Robert Herjavec, the son
of an immigrant factory worker,

00:01:36,320 --> 00:01:38,200
is now a technology mogul

00:01:38,200 --> 00:01:40,170
who sold his first
internet companies

00:01:40,170 --> 00:01:43,470
for over $350 million.

00:01:43,470 --> 00:01:45,380
And Mark Cuban,

00:01:45,380 --> 00:01:48,380
notorious billionaire
entrepreneur

00:01:48,380 --> 00:01:51,100
and the outspoken owner
of the Dallas Mavericks.

00:02:02,200 --> 00:02:03,430
First in is Aly Lessor,

00:02:03,430 --> 00:02:07,100
with a business inspired
by her daughter Cosette.

00:02:16,330 --> 00:02:19,020
Hi, sharks.
My name is Aly Lessor,

00:02:19,020 --> 00:02:20,100
and I'm the creator

00:02:20,100 --> 00:02:23,080
of the children's clothing line
Cozy Bug.

00:02:23,080 --> 00:02:25,180
I'm asking for $50,000

00:02:25,180 --> 00:02:28,080
in exchange for
25% of my company.

00:02:28,080 --> 00:02:32,030
Most kids outgrow their clothes
every season,

00:02:32,030 --> 00:02:34,170
and it gets really expensive.

00:02:34,170 --> 00:02:38,170
However, our pillowcase dresses
grow with the kids.

00:02:38,170 --> 00:02:39,350
And the way
they're designed,

00:02:39,350 --> 00:02:41,230
they cinch here
at the neck,

00:02:41,230 --> 00:02:43,200
and then we use
these beautiful ribbons

00:02:43,200 --> 00:02:44,480
that tie at the shoulder,

00:02:44,480 --> 00:02:46,420
allowing for growth
under the arm

00:02:46,420 --> 00:02:48,080
and in length.

00:02:48,080 --> 00:02:50,480
Now eventually,
the kids sprout so much,

00:02:50,480 --> 00:02:52,120
and then you just put on

00:02:52,120 --> 00:02:54,070
an adorable pair
of leggings or shorts

00:02:54,070 --> 00:02:57,070
and you have another outfit
for years to come.

00:02:57,070 --> 00:02:59,070
Cosette is 4 years old,

00:02:59,070 --> 00:03:00,450
and she's in
a size 4.

00:03:00,450 --> 00:03:03,120
This is Morgan,
who's 8 years old,

00:03:03,120 --> 00:03:05,180
and she is still
in a size 4.

00:03:05,180 --> 00:03:08,330
I'm a Southern girl
now living in Los Angeles,

00:03:08,330 --> 00:03:10,380
and my mother-In-law
in Alabama

00:03:10,380 --> 00:03:12,150
started mailing us
the most adorable

00:03:12,150 --> 00:03:14,270
monogrammed pillowcase
dresses

00:03:14,270 --> 00:03:16,380
for my daughter Cosette.

00:03:16,380 --> 00:03:18,430
Cosette is Cozy Bug.
That's her nickname.

00:03:18,430 --> 00:03:21,250
And whenever she wore them,
we would literally get stopped

00:03:21,250 --> 00:03:24,220
four to five times a day
by moms saying,

00:03:24,220 --> 00:03:26,230
"Where did you get
that outfit?"

00:03:26,230 --> 00:03:30,050
and that's when I decided
to pillowcase the world.

00:03:30,050 --> 00:03:33,400
Our pillowcase dresses are not
actually made from pillowcases.

00:03:33,400 --> 00:03:36,370
We use really fun,
vibrant fabrics.

00:03:36,370 --> 00:03:39,330
We have jackets, jeggings,
shirts,

00:03:39,330 --> 00:03:42,250
and of course every outfit
needs a matching hair bow,

00:03:42,250 --> 00:03:45,080
which we've sold
thousands of.

00:03:45,080 --> 00:03:47,430
I have taken Cozy Bug
just about as far as I can

00:03:47,430 --> 00:03:49,180
with my contacts.

00:03:49,180 --> 00:03:51,220
With your help
and expertise,

00:03:51,220 --> 00:03:53,350
we can make Cozy Bug
an international brand

00:03:53,350 --> 00:03:56,170
and take it places
I could only imagine.

00:03:56,170 --> 00:03:57,400
So come on, sharks.

00:03:57,400 --> 00:03:59,350
Who's ready to pillowcase
the world?

00:03:59,350 --> 00:04:02,180
Aw!
(sharks laugh)

00:04:02,180 --> 00:04:04,200
Okay, thank you, girls.
Say bye to the sharks.

00:04:04,200 --> 00:04:05,420
Bye, sharks!
(Lori) Bye!

00:04:05,420 --> 00:04:07,330
(Mark) See ya!
(men) Bye!

00:04:07,330 --> 00:04:09,150
Aw. (laughs)

00:04:09,150 --> 00:04:11,200
I'm in.
(laughter)

00:04:11,200 --> 00:04:14,400
(laughs)
Is the concept
of a pillowcase dress

00:04:14,400 --> 00:04:16,320
something that's been around
in the south forever,

00:04:16,320 --> 00:04:18,000
as you said?
It has, yes.

00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:19,050
(Lori) Oh, really?
Yeah.

00:04:19,050 --> 00:04:20,450
How many people
are in your company?

00:04:20,450 --> 00:04:21,450
Me.

00:04:21,450 --> 00:04:23,170
Just you?
Yeah.

00:04:23,170 --> 00:04:25,070
(Robert)
What's your background?

00:04:25,070 --> 00:04:28,280
I was in sales. I've been
in sales for 20 years.

00:04:28,280 --> 00:04:31,000
And had my daughter Cosette.

00:04:31,000 --> 00:04:34,420
And they were not letting me
pump my breast milk at work.

00:04:34,420 --> 00:04:38,170
And I told my 26-year-old
female manager,

00:04:38,170 --> 00:04:40,100
"I need to pump,"
and she's like,

00:04:40,100 --> 00:04:41,430
"Oh, we don't have time
for that right now.

00:04:41,430 --> 00:04:43,250
You're gonna have to wait."

00:04:43,250 --> 00:04:45,080
So I told my manager,
"I'm sorry.

00:04:45,080 --> 00:04:46,430
I have to go do this
right now."

00:04:46,430 --> 00:04:48,330
And she's like, "you can get
your stuff and go home."

00:04:48,330 --> 00:04:50,020
Fired me--
Oh, my--

00:04:50,020 --> 00:04:51,150
Wow.
Really?

00:04:51,150 --> 00:04:52,330
Yes. And, uh...
come on.

00:04:52,330 --> 00:04:55,330
Yes, so I sued her, won,

00:04:55,330 --> 00:04:58,000
and I had money
to start my company.

00:04:58,000 --> 00:04:59,170
Wow, good for you.
I love that.

00:04:59,170 --> 00:05:00,470
I love that.
Outstanding. Great story.

00:05:00,470 --> 00:05:02,200
I can't believe somebody
would say that to you. That's--

00:05:02,200 --> 00:05:03,430
I was like,
what year are we in?

00:05:03,430 --> 00:05:05,330
A female, at that.

00:05:05,330 --> 00:05:09,150
What does it cost you
to make one pillowcase dress?

00:05:09,150 --> 00:05:10,430
$6.
$6.

00:05:10,430 --> 00:05:12,430
With fabric
and manufacturing.

00:05:12,430 --> 00:05:14,450
I know you guys could get
that done a lot cheaper.

00:05:14,450 --> 00:05:16,320
(chuckles)
Where are you selling?

00:05:16,320 --> 00:05:19,250
The main place we sell
is online.

00:05:19,250 --> 00:05:23,150
In just 30 days,
we sold over $300,000...

00:05:23,150 --> 00:05:24,320
Whoa. Oh.
Worth of dresses.

00:05:24,320 --> 00:05:26,030
Oh. Really?

00:05:26,030 --> 00:05:27,220
The Web site that I sell on--

00:05:27,220 --> 00:05:29,030
Have you guys heard of
zulily?

00:05:29,030 --> 00:05:30,370
So you're allowed
to go on there

00:05:30,370 --> 00:05:32,470
three days every month.

00:05:32,470 --> 00:05:35,100
And within 30 days
of being on there,

00:05:35,100 --> 00:05:36,280
$300,000.

00:05:36,280 --> 00:05:38,080
Ooh!

00:05:38,080 --> 00:05:41,050
We also just launched
our own dancewear line

00:05:41,050 --> 00:05:42,270
called Dance Bug.

00:05:42,270 --> 00:05:45,170
We sell tutus and all that.

00:05:45,170 --> 00:05:47,000
(Kevin) Why,
when you know you've found

00:05:47,000 --> 00:05:48,230
this remarkable niche,

00:05:48,230 --> 00:05:50,200
would you want to bother
competing

00:05:50,200 --> 00:05:52,200
with everybody else
in the children's lines,

00:05:52,200 --> 00:05:55,120
making, you know,
ballerina dresses and coats?

00:05:55,120 --> 00:05:56,230
Kevin's right.
So you think just this?

00:05:56,230 --> 00:05:57,350
You've got--You've got
the ability

00:05:57,350 --> 00:06:00,130
to differentiate yourself
from everybody,

00:06:00,130 --> 00:06:02,180
and it's making you
a boatload of money.

00:06:02,180 --> 00:06:03,450
Why not be great
at one thing?

00:06:03,450 --> 00:06:06,170
I don't agree with that,
because this is

00:06:06,170 --> 00:06:08,250
a fashion item--
'cause it doesn't work
on QVC, that's why.

00:06:08,250 --> 00:06:11,000
If mark knew about fashion,
he would know that women,

00:06:11,000 --> 00:06:13,070
when you start with something
and it's a great concept

00:06:13,070 --> 00:06:15,000
and people are loving it,
they want more.

00:06:15,000 --> 00:06:16,330
And that's how businesses
continue to grow

00:06:16,330 --> 00:06:18,370
and grow and grow.

00:06:18,370 --> 00:06:21,070
So you are very smart to--
That's also how businesses
go out of business as well.

00:06:21,070 --> 00:06:22,270
They try to get too wide--
All of these--

00:06:22,270 --> 00:06:24,170
Nothing great.
Well, maybe,
But not in fashion, Mark.

00:06:24,170 --> 00:06:26,350
In fashion--
Right, because so many fashion
companies just stay in business.

00:06:26,350 --> 00:06:29,000
They all stay in business.
None of them ever go out

00:06:29,000 --> 00:06:30,220
from expanding their lines
too quickly.

00:06:30,220 --> 00:06:32,070
But, Mark, you're not
in the fashion business.

00:06:34,020 --> 00:06:36,020
Okay, Aly, here--Here's
the way I see it.

00:06:36,020 --> 00:06:38,420
The biggest mistake many,
many entrepreneurs make

00:06:38,420 --> 00:06:41,000
is that they try to do
too much too soon.

00:06:41,000 --> 00:06:43,050
And it kills them
and they go out of business.

00:06:43,050 --> 00:06:46,320
I like to shoot for the stars.
I see me going everywhere.

00:06:46,320 --> 00:06:48,230
I'm glad you told me that,
because to me,

00:06:48,230 --> 00:06:50,130
it's better to dominate
at one thing

00:06:50,130 --> 00:06:51,380
and then build off of that.

00:06:51,380 --> 00:06:54,370
By going too wide,
typically companies drown.

00:06:54,370 --> 00:06:57,380
And so, for that reason,
I'm out.

00:06:57,380 --> 00:07:00,350
Okay. Thank you.
Thank you.

00:07:01,420 --> 00:07:03,380
I'm not here
just for money.

00:07:03,380 --> 00:07:05,180
I'm here for a partnership.

00:07:05,180 --> 00:07:09,470
I have tried countless times
to even get phone numbers

00:07:09,470 --> 00:07:13,200
or contacts of the buyers
at the big box stores.

00:07:13,200 --> 00:07:15,150
It's impossible.
It's a secret society.

00:07:16,250 --> 00:07:18,050
All right, let me--

00:07:18,050 --> 00:07:19,320
Let me clear
the field a little bit.

00:07:20,420 --> 00:07:23,270
I can't really offer you
the expertise

00:07:23,270 --> 00:07:26,450
in terms of what you're doing
and your expansion plans.

00:07:26,450 --> 00:07:28,230
Let me get out of the way.

00:07:28,230 --> 00:07:30,270
I'm out.
I wish you all the best.

00:07:38,300 --> 00:07:40,080
And I'll make you
an offer, okay?

00:07:40,080 --> 00:07:42,130
Because you're unique.

00:07:42,130 --> 00:07:43,320
I'll give you $50,000,

00:07:43,320 --> 00:07:45,320
and here's how much equity
I want in your business.

00:07:45,320 --> 00:07:48,350
Zero. Okay?

00:07:48,350 --> 00:07:51,080
You're gonna pay me
$2 a dress

00:07:51,080 --> 00:07:52,330
until I get my 50k back,

00:07:52,330 --> 00:07:55,350
and then you're gonna pay me
$1 forever after that.

00:07:55,350 --> 00:07:57,170
Here's the covenant.

00:07:57,170 --> 00:08:00,370
I forbid you to make anything
except hair bows

00:08:00,370 --> 00:08:02,150
and pillowcase dresses.

00:08:02,150 --> 00:08:04,350
Every dress does need
a hair bow. (laughs)

00:08:04,350 --> 00:08:06,430
(laughter)
It's true.

00:08:06,430 --> 00:08:09,270
Last season,
I took a woman

00:08:09,270 --> 00:08:11,350
who came in with a towel
with a slit in it.

00:08:11,350 --> 00:08:14,170
Mr. Wonderful said
It was insane.

00:08:14,170 --> 00:08:15,430
It was madness.

00:08:15,430 --> 00:08:18,050
And to date, we're
in the Disney theme parks,

00:08:18,050 --> 00:08:20,420
all over, with that towel
with the slit in it.

00:08:20,420 --> 00:08:23,330
I'm going to offer you
the $50,000...

00:08:25,350 --> 00:08:28,170
Take 30% stake in the company,

00:08:28,170 --> 00:08:31,020
and take this nationwide.

00:08:31,020 --> 00:08:32,480
And not just on QVC,

00:08:32,480 --> 00:08:34,480
but we can take it
into all the retailers,

00:08:34,480 --> 00:08:37,120
and I think that I can
make you a millionaire

00:08:37,120 --> 00:08:38,330
with this line.

00:08:40,200 --> 00:08:43,030
Here's why that's
a bad idea.

00:08:43,030 --> 00:08:46,000
If you go the route
that Lori's suggesting,

00:08:46,000 --> 00:08:48,220
you don't make enough money
to sell to retailers--
Excuse me.

00:08:48,220 --> 00:08:50,250
Silence.

00:08:50,250 --> 00:08:52,130
You're the silent partner.
Here's what's--

00:08:52,130 --> 00:08:54,050
Here's what's good about
what I'm doing for you.

00:08:54,050 --> 00:08:57,370
I am forcing you into
a tunnel of profitability,

00:08:57,370 --> 00:09:00,330
where every time you get up
in the morning and make a sale,

00:09:00,330 --> 00:09:03,170
you make money.
That's a grand plan,

00:09:03,170 --> 00:09:05,100
kind of like the "titanic."
And that is the only plan.

00:09:05,100 --> 00:09:07,280
(Daymond)
Let me just, uh...

00:09:07,280 --> 00:09:09,250
don't even get involved.

00:09:09,250 --> 00:09:13,130
I'm just gonna take
the deal. Um...
(laughs)

00:09:13,130 --> 00:09:14,450
This is my area.

00:09:16,430 --> 00:09:18,250
I know I can make you
the millionaire quicker.

00:09:21,230 --> 00:09:24,070
I'm gonna offer you
the $50,000 for 30%--

00:09:24,070 --> 00:09:25,430
The same thing as Lori's.

00:09:25,430 --> 00:09:29,200
And your avenue would be to
get it in the retail stores?

00:09:29,200 --> 00:09:31,400
That's the only value
that I would bring to it,

00:09:31,400 --> 00:09:33,420
is to roll it out to retail,
to roll it out quick,

00:09:33,420 --> 00:09:35,100
to roll it out globally,

00:09:35,100 --> 00:09:37,130
and bring you into my system
and distribute it.

00:09:37,130 --> 00:09:39,230
(Lori) And I can do
all of the above...
(Kevin) Aly, these--

00:09:39,230 --> 00:09:41,070
Just the same and more.
(Kevin speaks Indistinctly)

00:09:41,070 --> 00:09:42,220
Wait a minute, wait.
Stop, stop, stop.

00:09:42,220 --> 00:09:44,200
I have to clarify one thing,
because if you go with her,

00:09:44,200 --> 00:09:46,370
right after she sells
hemorrhoid cream,

00:09:46,370 --> 00:09:49,250
she'll sell your stuff and then
dental cream or something else.

00:09:49,250 --> 00:09:51,250
We are not all--
Who knows what he's
even talking about?

00:09:51,250 --> 00:09:52,400
We are not all--listen.

00:09:52,400 --> 00:09:55,330
I know how to do
what you want to be done.

00:09:55,330 --> 00:09:58,180
Daymond, I just passed
a lemonade stand this morning

00:09:58,180 --> 00:10:00,180
that sells more product
than you.

00:10:00,180 --> 00:10:01,200
Whoa! (laughs)
Ow.

00:10:01,200 --> 00:10:02,220
I know.

00:10:02,220 --> 00:10:03,400
I did $6 billion.

00:10:03,400 --> 00:10:05,080
B-B-B-Billion.

00:10:05,080 --> 00:10:07,380
I did $500 million
with walmart This year.

00:10:07,380 --> 00:10:09,420
You're selling dresses
for little girls.

00:10:09,420 --> 00:10:12,270
Who do you think
is a better partner

00:10:12,270 --> 00:10:14,370
to make clothing
for little girls?

00:10:14,370 --> 00:10:16,180
(Daymond) I have
two daughters.

00:10:16,180 --> 00:10:18,070
I did $1 billion
in kids' clothing alone.

00:10:18,070 --> 00:10:21,170
Would you guys,
Lori and Daymond,

00:10:21,170 --> 00:10:24,000
ever want to do
a sweetheart deal,

00:10:24,000 --> 00:10:25,150
where we all work together?

00:10:25,150 --> 00:10:26,380
No.

00:10:26,380 --> 00:10:29,200
I don't want it on QVC.
Okay. Okay.

00:10:29,200 --> 00:10:30,450
I do not want it on QVC...
okay.

00:10:30,450 --> 00:10:32,230
And I don't think you should
have it on QVC.
Okay.

00:10:32,230 --> 00:10:34,220
You gotta start making
some decisions.

00:10:34,220 --> 00:10:36,430
So what are you gonna do?

00:10:38,330 --> 00:10:41,270
♪♪♪

00:10:45,750 --> 00:10:47,667
♪♪♪

00:10:47,667 --> 00:10:49,667
Aly has three offers
on the table.

00:10:49,667 --> 00:10:53,307
Kevin's offer--
$50,000 for zero equity,

00:10:53,307 --> 00:10:55,487
but a royalty
for every dress sold.

00:10:55,487 --> 00:10:58,367
And competing offers
from Lori and Daymond,

00:10:58,367 --> 00:11:01,617
each offering $50,000
for 30% equity.

